===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|犬|里|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=dog}}. Originally an unorthodox variant ({{zh-l|*俗字}}) of the character {{zh-l|*貍|lí}}.

===Etymology===
{{unc|zh}}. Here some proposals:
* ''{{w|Fangyan (book)|Fangyan}}'' [https://ctext.org/dictionary.pl?if=en&id=45515] and {{w|Guo Pu}} consider it to be one among many dialectal words for {{och-l|貔}}, which however is a different word ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}) (see there).
* {{zh-ref|Zhao & Huang (1998)}} (apud {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}) connects it to {{cog|hmn|-}} ''pli'' ~ ''ple'' "cat".
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} minimally reconstructs {{och-l|貍|tr=*rə}} from *''pʰrə'' ~ *''pʰə-rə'' and proposes possible {{der|zh|sit}} etymology and compares it to {{cog|mro|pri||a kind of leopard}} (see also {{zh-ref|Löffler, 1966}}); he also sees potential cognacy with {{cog|bo|ཞི་མི}}, {{m|bo|ཞིམ་བུ}}, {{m|bo|ཞུམ་བུ}} - all meaning "cat" - if those were from *''ryi-mi''; additionally, {{m|bo|པི་ཤི||cat}} (< *''zhi''?) is possibly equivalent to Old Chinese dialectal forms with initial *''pʰ-'' (e.g. {{zh-l|𧳏|tr=pī}} < {{w|Eastern Han Chinese|LHC}} *''pʰiə'' < OC *''pʰrə'' or {{zh-l|𧳏貍|tr=pīlí}}); in that case, the original Chinese word might have been a compound: {{zh-l|貔狸}} "(large) cat and small cat"; even so, see {{och-l|貔}} for possible Indic influence on Tibetan ''byi'' ~ ''pi'' ([[ibid.]]).
* STEDT reconstructs {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-(l/r)e(y/ŋ)||squirrel, weasel}} and proposes cognacy with {{och-l|鼪}}, {{cog|bo|'''སྲེ'''་མོང||weasel}}, {{cog|my|ရှဉ့်||squirrel}}, etc.

